  <section id="faq" class="container-wide py-20">
    <span class="eyebrow">FAQ</span>
    <h2 class="mt-3 font-display text-3xl font-bold grad-text sm:text-4xl">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="mt-10 max-w-3xl divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>What makes a GEO tool worth using in 2026?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 11-2 0v-3H6a1 1 0 110-2h3V6a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">In 2026, a GEO tool earns its place in a stack if it measures something that genuinely cannot be measured by a traditional SEO platform. The minimum threshold is real AI platform coverage across ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, and Copilot. Beyond that, tools are worth their cost if they offer reliable historical data retention, prompt customisation, citation-level granularity, and transparent methodology. The market has matured enough that superficial tools with AI-era branding but no substantive measurement capability are now easier to identify and avoid.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>How is the GEO tool landscape different in 2026 compared to 2024?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">The GEO tool market has consolidated meaningfully since 2024. Early entrants with weak data methodology have largely dropped away, and category leaders have invested in multi-platform coverage, competitive benchmarking, and API access for enterprise clients. Established SEO platforms — notably Semrush, Ahrefs, and Authoritas — have added AI visibility features, blurring the line between dedicated GEO tools and traditional SEO suites. The measurement rigour of purpose-built GEO tools still generally exceeds that of add-on features.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>Should I use one GEO platform or combine multiple tools?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Most mature GEO programmes use at least two distinct tools: one dedicated AI citation monitoring platform for the core measurement task, and one or more specialist tools for entity analysis and content optimisation. No single platform does everything well in 2026. The most common combination is a dedicated monitoring platform plus an entity analysis tool. Traditional SEO tools remain useful for the foundational work that underpins GEO performance.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>How often should I reassess which GEO tools I use?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Annual reassessment is a reasonable minimum, given how quickly the category moves. The most important moments to reassess are when a major AI platform changes its architecture or retrieval system, when a competitor makes a significant GEO tool investment, and when your own programme matures past the stage your current tooling was designed to serve. Always supplement annual roundups like this one with direct vendor trials and current user community feedback.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button type="button" class="flex w-full items-center justify-between py-5 text-left font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink-100 hover:text-[var(--accent)] transition-colors" aria-expanded="false">
          <span>Are free GEO tools adequate for a serious programme?</span>
          <svg class="faq-icon ml-4 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-ink-500 transition-transform duration-200" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10 5a1 1 0 011 1v3h3a1 1 0 110 2h-3v3a1 1 0 011-1z"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height:0">
          <p class="pb-5 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Free and free-tier GEO tools are adequate for establishing a baseline and learning the discipline, but they have real limitations for ongoing programmes. Most free options offer restricted query volumes, limited historical data retention, and no competitive benchmarking. For a brand serious about GEO as an ongoing performance channel, a paid monitoring platform is eventually necessary. Start with free tools to establish your measurement process, then upgrade once you have a repeatable workflow that justifies the investment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

